720398f-a.text:

720399f-a.title: Manhattan: Broadway - 35th Street (West)
720399f-a.text:
Broadway, east side, north from West 35th Street (Right)
showing prominently the newly erected Herald Building.
This replaced the old 71st Irf. Regiment Armory. Note
the absence of the tri-figured ''Bell Ringers'' that was
mounted in 1895 atop the Herald Building.
About 1893-4
H. N. Tiemann, photo

717410f-a.title: Manhattan: Broadway - 35th Street (West)
717410f-a.text:
Broadway, west side, from West 35th to 36th Street's,
showing prominently the Herald Souare Theatre. This is
at the N.W. corner of 35th Street. It was first opened
in 1883 as the New Park. Later Harrigan took a lease
and produced ''01d Lavender'',''Pote'' and other successes.
The name was changed to that shown in 1895. The follow-
ing year Belasco's play 'THHe Heart of Maryland'' was pro-
duced here. Lew Fields was the final lessee. The house
was toen down in 1912.
At the left and right margins respectively appear Macys
Department Store and the Hotel Marlborough. Slightly to
the right of the former is the Arsenal tower at Seventh Ave.
About 1910
H. N. Tiemenn, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection
